        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Sensitivity: The continuum flux of this source is known from 2mm, 850um, 500um, 350um and 250um. We are aiming to do a spectral scan over 130-160GHz, reaching 5-sigma in continuum in 30 km/s channels. Therefore we base our sensitivity assuming 130 GHz as the representative frequency, where the flux density is 8mJy. We therefore require a sensitivity of 1.6mJy for a 5-sigma detection in a 30 km/s channel.

Imaging: we will obtain an unresolved detection with the most compact configuration, and we do not expect any emission extended beyond the 3" beam (note that this is a galaxy-galaxy lens in the field of a cluster of galaxies).

Correlator setup: we chose a spectral scan with dual polarization products, covering 130-160GHz in 5 tunings. Using a bandwidth of 1.875 GHz (i.e. the coarsest spectral resolution FDM mode) and 0.976 MHz channel spacing (including online Hanning smoothing). We will bin the spectrum to a resolution of 30 km/s to search for emission lines (typical widths 200-300 km/s) against the continuum, and bin further (up to 100 km/s) to search for fainter or statistical emission features. The redshift is known precisely from existing CO line detections.

Calibration: standard.

Bandpass accuracy: although we will be searching for emission on a continuuum, some features of which may be faint, we do not require very high spectral response accuracies in this exploration experiment.

Data rate: the 12m data rate is 22 MB/s, which exceeds the policy value of 2x the average 6MB/s. The maximum data rate possible is 60 MB/s. Given the exploratory nature of our observation, which could be considered an excellent test of Band 4 spectral scanning for extragalactic sources, and the potentially high-yield of the scientific return (true discovery space), we believe the request for a data rate that is ~1/3 of the maximum is justified.

Special considerations: none.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
