    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>We propose for a full Band 4 spectral scan of an extremely bright, gravitationally lensed submillimetre galaxy (SMG) at z=2.87. The object was discovered in a dedicated 'snapshot' program with SCUBA-2 and Herschel, and its flux density ranks it amongst one of the brightest SMGs known (850um=130mJy). Here we propose an exploration experiment, obtaining the most detailed mm spectrum of a distant star-forming galaxy yet measured. We will detect the continuum emission across the full range 130-160GHz to a 5-sigma significance and search for the emission of several dense-gas tracers that lie in this range, including transitions of HCN, HCO+, HNC, CO, ammonia and CS, as well as their isotopologues. Some of these lines will never have been detected in the extragalactic Universe. Our aim is to examine the rich chemistry of the dense molecular phase in this galaxy, using the emission features to examine and constrain the average conditions of the dense gas actually fuelling star formation in a galaxy seen just two billion years after the Big Bang. </prp:abstract>
